":"1046–Afdød","1050–Female":"1050–Afdød","1132":"1132","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1192":"1192","1070":"1070","1104":"1104","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","1101":"1101","1178":"1178","1111":"1111","1144":"1144","before 1062":"før 1062","about 1102":"omkring 1102","Wales":"Wales","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales":"Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Maes Gwenllian, Wales":"Maes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1070–1132":"1070–1132","1065–1144":"1065–1144","1066–1178":"1066–1178","1101–Male":"1101–Overleden","1051–1111":"1051–1111","1102–Male":"1102–Overleden","1104–1192":"1104–1192","–Male":"Overleden","1046–Male":"1046–Overleden","1050–Female":"1050–Overleden","1132":"1132","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1192":"1192","1070":"1070","1104":"1104","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","1101":"1101","1178":"1178","1111":"1111","1144":"1144","before 1062":"vóór 1062","about 1102":"circa 1102","Wales":"Wales","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales":"Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Maes Gwenllian, Wales":"Maes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1070–1132":"1070–1132","1065–1144":"1065–1144","1066–1178":"1066–1178","1101–Male":"1101–Deceased","1051–1111":"1051–1111","1102–Male":"1102–Deceased","1104–1192":"1104–1192","–Male":"Deceased","1046–Male":"1046–Deceased","1050–Female":"1050–Deceased","1132":"1132","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1192":"1192","1070":"1070","1104":"1104","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","1101":"1101","1178":"1178","1111":"1111","1144":"1144","before 1062":"before 1062","about 1102":"about 1102","Wales":"Wales","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales":"Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Maes Gwenllian, Wales":"Maes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Picot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Francois, Jacques, Jeanpaul, Luc, Pascal, Yves.  Spanish Esperanza, Aida, Alicia, Ana, Felipe, Luis.","French: from Old French <i>picot</i> ‘pointed object, pickaxe’, a nickname for someone who used such an implement. This surname is also found in Haiti.","Catalan: nickname from Valencian dialect <i>picot</i> ‘(sheep or goat) bell’."],"variants":[{"name":"Pickett","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Picot</i>, <i>Pigot</i>, a pet form of <i>Pic</i> (see   Pike   6). In Middle English, the form <i>Piket</i> (Old French <i>Picquet</i>) was also common.","sometimes a late development of   Pickard   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Picotte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Honore, Andre, Jacques, Serge.","Altered form of French   Picot  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Say","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Sai in Orne or Say in Indre, France, perhaps so called from a Gaulish personal name <i>Saius</i> + the Latin locative suffix <i>-acum</i> (see also French name 3 below).","English: nickname, perhaps for someone who made or sold say, a type of woollen cloth, or for an habitual wearer of clothes made of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."],"variants":[{"name":"Sey","meanings":["English and Scottish: probably a variant of   Say   particularly prevalent in Scotland.","Dutch and Flemish: from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigiheri</i> (see   Seger  ).","West African (Ghana): Akan (Fante) name of unexplained etymology."]},{"name":"Sayer","meanings":["English: common occupational name from Middle English <i>sayer</i>, a phonetic variant of   Sawyer  , which in Wales and neighboring English counties may have been reinforced by the synonymous Welsh <i>saer</i> ‘carpenter’ and everywhere by a possible borrowing into Middle English of Old French <i>seieor</i>, <i>saieur</i> ‘sawyer’.","English: rare occupational name perhaps denoting an assayer of metals, or a servant who tasted his lord's food before serving, from Middle English <i>saiour</i> ‘assayer, tester’ (a shortened form of Old French <i>assaiour</i>, ultimately from Late Latin <i>exagium</i>, a derivative of <i>exagmināre</i> ‘to weigh’).","English: rare occupational name for a professional reciter or minstrel, from Middle English <i>seier(e)</i> ‘speaker’."]},{"name":"Saye","meanings":["English: variant of   Say  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Saje</b>: nickname for someone with very dark, sooty hair, derived from the root of <i>sajast</i> ‘sooty’, or directly from <i>saja</i> ‘soot’.","West African (Liberia): from the personal name <i>Saye</i>, found among the Mano (Mah) people, denoting a first-born boy."]}]},{"name":"Daughter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Dawtrey</b>, see   Daughtry   and also   Daughters  . The surname is most common in Yorkshire and Sussex, where the medieval <i>Dawtrey</i> family held lands in the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Daughters","meanings":["English (London): variant of <b>Dafter</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, apparently from Middle English <i>doughter</i>, <i>dohtor</i>, <i>douter</i> (Old English <i>dohtor</i>) ‘daughter’, often pronounced in early modern English as <i>dafter</i>. For the name to be borne by a man, such that it became a hereditary surname, is surprising, though there are occasional instances of men being named in this way (unless they are clerical errors or it was a surname acquired by the retainers of an heiress of an important family). Alternatively, alternatively <i>Daughter</i>, <i>Daughters</i> might be a simplified pronunciation of <b>Dawtry</b> (see   Daughtery  ), a surname well evidenced in Yorkshire and Sussex, where <i>Doughter</i> and <i>Daughter</i> also occur, in which case the change to <i>Dafter</i> will have arisen through misinterpretation."]},{"name":"Daughtry","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Dawtrey</b>, a habitational name with fused French preposition <i>d(e)</i>, for someone from Hauterive in Orne, France, named from Old French <i>haute rive</i> ‘high bank’ (rendered into Latin <i>Alta Ripa</i>). The medieval <i>Dawtrey</i> family had lands in Yorkshire, Lincolnshire, and Sussex in the 12th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Unnamed Daughter Picot de Say was born in 1070, her father, Robert fitz Picot de Say Lord of Clun, Vicomte, was 25 and her mother, Unnamed Wife de Saye, was 21. She had at least 3 sons with Cadwgan ap Bleddyn. She died in 1132, in Maes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1070–1132":"1070–1132","1065–1144":"1065–1144","1066–1178":"1066–1178","1101–Male":"1101–Surnud","1051–1111":"1051–1111","1102–Male":"1102–Surnud","1104–1192":"1104–1192","–Male":"Surnud","1046–Male":"1046–Surnud","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1132":"1132","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1192":"1192","1070":"1070","1104":"1104","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","1101":"1101","1178":"1178","1111":"1111","1144":"1144","before 1062":"enne 1062","about 1102":"umbes 1102","Wales":"Wales","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales":"Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Maes Gwenllian, Wales":"Maes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1070–1132":"1070–1132","1065–1144":"1065–1144","1066–1178":"1066–1178","1101–Male":"1101–Kuollut","1051–1111":"1051–1111","1102–Male":"1102–Kuollut","1104–1192":"1104–1192","–Male":"Kuollut","1046–Male":"1046–Kuollut","1050–Female":"1050–Kuollut","1132":"1132","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1192":"1192","1070":"1070","1104":"1104","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","1101":"1101","1178":"1178","1111":"1111","1144":"1144","before 1062":"ennen vuotta 1062","about 1102":"noin 1102","Wales":"Wales","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales":"Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Maes Gwenllian, Wales":"Maes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1070–1132":"1070–1132","1065–1144":"1065–1144","1066–1178":"1066–1178","1101–Male":"1101–Décédé","1051–1111":"1051–1111","1102–Male":"1102–Décédé","1104–1192":"1104–1192","–Male":"Décédé","1046–Male":"1046–Décédé","1050–Female":"1050–Décédée","1132":"1132","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1051":"1051","1050":"1050","1